observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE): 

Require the Inventory Committee (IC) to complete the annual physical inventory of all PPE items and mobilize additional competent personnel from other departments to assist and facilitate the conduct thereof; 

Require the Municipal Accountant’s Office (MAO) to maintain Construction in Progress (CIP) Ledger Card and complete and updated PPELCs to support General Ledger (GL) accounts balance and the Municipal General Services Office (MGSO) to keep corresponding PCs for control purposes;  

Strengthen the controls on the handling and recording procedures for the PPE accounts by performing periodic reconciliation of records between the MGSO and MAO and ensure that any discrepancies noted are immediately investigated and adjusted in the books accordingly; and 

Consider applying the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts per COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to:
Direct the MA to furnish each department with a list of PPE assigned to them.  In turn, department heads to conduct an initial physical inventory of all items located within their offices and submit the results to the designated MGSO for the preparation and updating of PCs;
Instruct the designated MGSO to reconcile his property records with those of the MA and to consolidate and submit the reconciled report to the IC;
Require the MA to recognize the depreciation expense for assets previously recorded without depreciation.  Also, direct the MA to closely coordinate with the MGSO in reconciling their respective PPE records.  The PPELC must be updated with complete and specific details, avoiding lump-sum entries such as 'various offices', and instead reflect individual, itemized assets with full specifications to ensure proper tracking and accountability;
Enjoin the Municipal Engineer to assist the IC in conducting the physical count and documentation of infrastructure assets, including roads, buildings, and other structures;
Direct the IC to complete the annual physical inventory of all PPE items.  Additional competent personnel from other departments should be mobilized to support and expedite the conduct of the physical count;
After the completion of the RPCPPE by the IC, instruct both the MA and the MGSO to once again reconcile their respective records and update all relevant PCs and PPELCs accordingly;
Consider the implementation of the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts as provided under Commission on Audit (COA) Circular No. 2020-006, to establish PPE balances that are verifiable in terms of existence, condition, and accountability; and
Encourage the designated MGSO and members of the IC to attend relevant trainings and seminars on PPE management to enhance their technical knowledge and capacity in maintaining accurate and compliant property records.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
Require the designated MGSO to prepare and maintain individual SCs for each type of supply and material, and to conduct a semi-annual physical inventory in coordination with the IC.  The results should be properly documented using the prescribed RPCI format and submitted to the MA and the AT;
Instruct all end-user departments and offices to submit all received supplies to the MGSO for initial recording in the stock records and it should be accompanied by a RIS signed by the recipient office;
Instruct the MGSO to consolidate all RIS into a SSMI on a monthly basis, and to submit the SSMI promptly to the MA as basis for the recognition of expense and adjustment of inventory balances;
Require the MA to maintain SLCs based on the submitted SSMIs, and to recognize the supplies and materials as expenses once issued and consumed, in compliance with the accounting standards for inventory accounting;
Direct the MGSO and the MA to jointly reconcile their inventory records every quarter, to ensure consistency between (RPCI, SCs, SLCs, and accounting records;
Allocate or identify a temporary central storage area for supplies and materials, even if limited in size, to allow the MGSO to record all deliveries before distribution.  If storage is not feasible, the LGU may consider implementing a direct delivery but centralized recording system, where the MGSO still documents and logs the delivery and issuance even when the items are delivered straight to the end-user; and
Facilitate training for both MGSO and Accounting personnel on proper inventory management and documentation procedures, particularly with the use of SCs, RIS, SSMI, and physical inventory reporting.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to:
Direct the MA to review the ₱131,785.52 prior-year balance by examining available old records, previous turnovers, or related documents to determine the source or AOs;
Institute strict controls over cash collection and deposit processes by issuing a formal directive reminding the MT to fully comply with Section 313 of RA No. 7160 and relevant COA rules, ensuring that all collections are deposited intact daily or not later than the next banking day;
Require the MTO to prepare and regularly submit a reconciliation report comparing daily collections with daily deposits and have the M A review these reconciliations to reinforce accountability; and
Facilitate capacity-building or refresher training for municipal collection and accounting staff on proper cash handling, government accounting procedures, and compliance with legal deposit timelines, to strengthen staff awareness and competence.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Require the MA to strictly comply with the prescribed timeline for the preparation and submission of the BRS, in accordance with COA Circular No. 96-011;
Instruct the MA to make the necessary adjustments in the books to correct reconciling items such as stale checks and long-outstanding DITs;
Direct the MT to immediately notify the concerned payees of checks nearing staleness and advise them to request replacement checks, in accordance with Section 59 of the MNGAS for LGUs;
Require the MT to verify and confirm the status of deposits in transit with the bank and coordinate with the MA for proper recording;
Encourage close coordination between the MT and the MA to ensure that reconciling items are addressed promptly and that records are updated accurately and consistently; and
Require both offices to conduct a monthly joint review of bank reconciliation results to resolve any discrepancies and maintain accurate cash balances.

We commended the Municipality for its effective management and utilization of the substantial portion of funds received from NGAs.  The timely release of funds, clear program direction, and strong coordination among offices demonstrated a high level of commitment to transparency and accountability.
However, regarding the unutilized balance of ₱700,273.95, we recommended and the LCE agreed to take the following actions:
Coordinate with the RHU Office to promptly accelerate planning and implementation for the MCP NBS and e-Konsulta accounts, ensuring timely utilization within CY 2025;
Expedite verification with DOH and PhilHealth to determine the appropriate course of action for their fund balances, facilitating proper use or accounting and preventing unnecessary delays;
Engage with NMIS immediately to clarify the guidelines for the Ante Mortem funds, ensuring proper compliance and timely utilization or disposition; and
Continue monitoring PCSO-related activities closely to support efficient use of the allocated funds within the intended timeframe.

We recommended and the SMMSB agreed to consider the following measures to strengthen its SEF planning and budgeting processes:
Follow strictly the prescribed timeline in the preparation of the annual SEF Budget as provided in DepEd-DBM-DILG JC No. 1, s. 2017;
Require the LSB to prepare the LSB three-year program, supported by approved individual SIPs and other information from DepEd Regional Office, prior to the preparation and approval of the SEF Budget and furnish the AT for reference and review purposes;
Support the SEF budget with plan of intended priority PPAs to be funded out of the fund presented by allotment class and per school; and
Require the MT, LSB and the MBO to coordinate properly so that accurate figures are included in the SEF Budget computation

We recommended that Management require:  

The General Services Officer and the MA to coordinate closely so that procurement and issuance of inventories will be properly recorded and presented in the Financial Statements (FS); 

The MGSO to prepare and submit the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) to the MA as basis for the preparation of Journal Entry Voucher to record the corresponding issued inventories; 

The MGSO to conduct the semestral physical inventory of supplies and materials and prepare the corresponding report thereon.  Furnish the Audit Team (AT) of the Report on the Physical Count of Inventories not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters inventory counts, respectively; and 

Conduct proper monitoring of inventory accounts to prevent thereof from exposure to possible misuse or loss through theft or misappropriation.

We recommended that Management:

Issue demand letters to all AOs concerned with outstanding CAs including those which were already separated from service.  Copy of the said demand letters bearing the proof of receipts of the concerned AOs should be furnished to the AT;

If warranted after review and evaluation, file a request for authority to write-off dormant unliquidated CAs to COA, duly supported with applicable documents and in accordance with the procedures prescribed in COA Circular No. 2016-005 for CAs of former officials and employees who are already deceased or cannot be located wherein the settlement/collectability of the same is unlikely.  Henceforth, adhere strictly with the governing law, rules and regulations on the grant, utilization and liquidation of CAs.

We recommended that Management:

Instruct the Bids and Awards Committee and the Municipal Engineer to plan properly and efficiently all procurement activities pertaining to developmental PPAs in order to fast-track the implementation and completion thereof; 

Require the MDC and all other implementing offices of the MGSM to step up its concerted efforts, ensure optimum utilization of the 20% DF and implement the PPAs within the targeted timeframe to achieve the timely delivery of desirable socio-economic development and environmental management outcome; 

Conduct an intensive review of continuing PPAs to determine those projects still feasibly implementable and reprogram to other priority development PPAs those that are considered inessential or undesirable; and

Consider assigning additional staff/personnel in the MEO to address the issue on lack of manpower, thus will hasten the preparation of POW and DCE.

We recommended that Management:

Require the Municipal Accountant to exert extra effort to properly identify the sources and status of implementation of the funds transferred by NGAs in the prior years, and prepare a comprehensive schedule for the same;

Revisit the prior years’ accounting entries made pertaining to the related Trust Fund transactions, and determine the possible erroneous entries made in order to ascertain the cause of the abnormal balance. Thereafter, effect the necessary adjustments in the books of accounts.

We recommended that Management:
Mobilize additional competent personnel from other departments to assist and facilitate the completion of the physical count of all PPE items;

Strengthen the controls on the handling and recording procedures for the PPE accounts by performing a periodic reconciliation of the records between the MGSO and Accounting Office and ensure that any discrepancies noted are immediately investigated and adjusted in the books accordingly;

Require the Office of the Municipal Accountant to maintain complete and updated PPELCs to support GL accounts balance and the MGSO to keep corresponding PCs for control purposes; and 

Require the Municipal Engineering Office to provide the needed data regarding the Infrastructure Asset accounts of the Municipality.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
Strictly monitor the conduct of regular and periodic verification, analysis and validation of the existence of receivable and payable accounts to ensure that only valid receivables and payables are recorded in the books;

Prepare a detailed schedule and ageing of receivables and payables once valid supporting documents are retrieved;

Document and file a request for authority to write-off dormant receivable accounts to COA as prescribed by the above cited Circular. Pending approval of such write-off, disclosed the actual account status in the Notes to FS to fairly present the receivable accounts in the FS; and

Prepare a certified schedule of ageing of dormant payable accounts for which there are no valid claimants/creditors and no supporting documents, and thereafter revert the verified amounts to the Unappropriated Surplus of the Government Equity Account by preparing the necessary Journal Entry Vouchers as basis for recording in the books of accounts of the Municipality.

We recommended that Management:
Prepare a three-year program indicating strategic prioritization policies in the allocation of the SEF to schools;

Gather and keep records of the information needed to be considered in the planning and budgeting for SEF, particularly the SIP and DEDP;

Consolidate the project proposals prepared and submitted by the School Heads for their respective SEF allocation which shall form part of the documentary support for the approval of the SEF Budget;

Ensure that the proposed PPAs presented in the SEF Budget are specifically identified as to name of the project, program and activity, allotment class and recipient school; and

Observe fully the policies in the planning and budgeting for SEF and the procedures and timelines in the preparation and approval of the budget for the said fund as stated in the DepEd, DBM and DILG JC No. 01, series of 2017.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to require, through the MT:
the collectors to remit promptly their collections to the MT in accordance with the prescribed period of remittance;
the collectors to prepare always the RCD every time they remit their collections to the MT and show the actual date of remittance;
the MT to always put the date of acceptance of the amount remitted by the collectors in the RCD for verification purposes;
the collectors to maintain updated cashbooks to monitor properly their collections and issuance of accountable forms;
the MT to monitor and enforce strictly the daily remittance of collections by revenue collectors to avoid accumulation of cash and possible loss thereof through theft or misappropriation; and
the MT to advise the BTs to remit regularly their respective collections due to the MGSM.
We also recommended and the LCE agreed to direct:
the MT to deposit all collections intact daily or not later than the next banking day to the AGDB pursuant to the pertinent regulations on the receipts and deposit of government monies;
the MA and the MT to prioritize the reconciliation of the Cash – Local Treasury account to come up with the correct balance thereof; and
the MA to present in the Notes to Financial Statements the undeposited collections of the current MT and the previous MT to avoid misinterpretation.
Further, we recommended and the LCE agreed to designate a permanent revenue collector for the WWS and procure additional computer equipment for the MTO to facilitate the preparation of collection reports.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to:
Instruct the MA and the MT to conduct monthly/quarterly/yearly reconciliation of their cash records to avoid discrepancies;
Direct the MA to obtain the necessary documents needed to support the identified reconciling items and draw Journal Entry Vouchers (JEV) to record all valid reconciling items that require adjustment/correction in the book.  Otherwise, open new bank account and present to the Notes to FS the noted reconciling items;
Require the MA to drop from the book of accounts the identified non-existing bank account;
Instruct the MA to communicate immediately to the concerned AGDBs any errors committed by the bank which were identified during the preparation of the BRS for correction; and
Require the MA to effect adjusting entries reverting the 11 stale checks equivalent to ₱85,171.68 to the Cash in Bank account of the LGU and restore the corresponding payable accounts thereof.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Compel the concerned AOs to settle immediately in full or refund their outstanding CAs, either by liquidation, by payment or through salary deductions;
Issue demand letters to all AOs concerned with outstanding CAs including those which were already separated from service.  Copy of the said demand letters bearing the receipts of the concerned accountable officials/employees should be furnished the AT;
Instruct the MA to draw the necessary correcting entries for the negative and/or erroneous balances due for adjustments; and
If warranted after review and evaluation, file request for authority to write-off dormant unliquidated CAs to COA, duly supported with applicable documents and in accordance with the procedures prescribed in COA Circular No. 2016-005 for CAs of former officials and employees who are already deceased or cannot be located wherein the settlement/collectability of the same is unlikely.  Henceforth, adhere strictly with the governing law, rules and regulations on the grant, utilization and liquidation of CAs.

We also recommended and the LCE agreed to direct the:
Concerned Offices to fast track the implementation of PPAs funded by the NGAs so that benefits attached thereto can be enjoyed by the recipients as soon as possible;
MA to reclassify the amount received from PCSO recorded from Due to NGAs to Subsidy from GOCC-PCSO;
Comply strictly with the requirements of MOA and/or general guidelines on the utilization and reporting of funds transferred by various NGAs.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to prioritize the reconciliation of the Cash in Bank accounts in order to come up with the correct balance;

Exert extra effort and obtain all the necessary documents needed to support the identified reconciling items and draw Journal Entry Vouchers (JEV) to record all valid reconciling items that require adjustment/correction in the book and ensure that the said reconciling items not to increase in the succeeding year;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to conduct a thorough review of records to determine the validity of long outstanding deposits in transit and make the necessary adjustments;

Ensure that any errors committed by the bank which were identified during the preparation of the BRS be immediately communicated to the concerned depository bank for correction; and

Require the Municipal Accountant to effect adjusting entries reverting the nine stale checks equivalent to ₱120,664.68 to the Cash in Bank account of the LGU and restore the corresponding payable accounts thereof.

We recommended that Management:
Compel the concerned AOs to immediately settle in full or refund their outstanding cash advances, either by liquidation, by payment or through salary deductions;

Issue demand letters to all AOs concerned with outstanding cash advances including those which were already separated from service. Copy of the said demand letters bearing the receipts of the concerned accountable officials/employees should be furnished the Audit Team;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to draw the necessary correcting entries for the negative and erroneous balances due for adjustments;

Devise other effective methods to increase the liquidation/payment rate and zero out outstanding cash advances; and

If warranted after review and evaluation, file request for authority to write-off dormant unliquidated cash advances to COA Office, duly supported with applicable documents and in accordance with the procedures prescribed in COA Circular No. 2016-005 for cash advances of former officials and employees who are already deceased or cannot be located wherein the settlement/collectability of the same is unlikely, and henceforth strictly adhere with the governing law, rules and regulations on the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Exert effort to trace and analyze the pertinent transactions in order to reconcile the variance of ₱0.92 million between the reciprocal accounts Due from/Due to Other Funds;

Thereafter, prepare the necessary adjusting entries to reflect the correct balances of the subject accounts; 

Ensure that the discrepancy between the reciprocal accounts balance be immediately eliminated, and if not, at least reduced in the ensuing year; and

Conduct periodic reconciliation of the reciprocal accounts in order to identify possible errors/adjustments which need to be adjusted in the books.

